<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-500-101  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 500 101.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Sept 17 1990 v7 n38 p38(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Business nets go to sea: how maritime companies use networkingtechnology to stay afloat.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The International Maritime Satellite Organization (INMARSAT)provides the majority of satellite services to ships.andP;  Theconsortium has eight satellites in operation; three primary andfive backup, over the Atlantic, Pacific and Indian oceans.andO;INMARSAT satellites provide services to more than 10,000 ships.andO;The satellites send telex, voice and data, including compressedvideo signals and facsimile, between ships and a worldwide networkof 20 coast earth stations.andP;  Voice and data messaging on satellitesystems is known as Mobile Satellite Service (MSS).andP;  Some usersfeel that satellites have higher reliability for sending data thanradio communications, but need to minimize the usage of satellitetransmissions because of the high cost.andP;  The INMARSAT satelliteswere launched by COMSAT, established by the US Congress in 1963.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Communications Satellite Corp. (communication systems).andO;Topic:     International Maritime Satellite OrganizationSatellite CommunicationsMaritime CommunicationsIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>